    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Echinacea Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Does echinacea actually work for colds?</summary><p>A Cochrane meta-analysis of 24 RCTs found echinacea may reduce cold duration by 1-2 days and risk by 10-20%. Results vary by species (E. purpurea is best studied), plant part, and extract quality. Not all products are equally effective.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Which echinacea species is most effective?</summary><p>E. purpurea aerial parts have the most clinical evidence. E. angustifolia root is traditional. E. pallida has less evidence. Combination products offer broader active compound profiles.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How should I take echinacea gummies?</summary><p>Prevention: daily during cold season. Acute: start within 24 hours of symptom onset, continue 7-10 days. Cycle: 8 weeks on, 1-2 weeks off to prevent immune tolerance.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take echinacea with other immune supplements?</summary><p>Yes. Echinacea, vitamin C, zinc, and elderberry work through different mechanisms and are complementary. Avoid combining with immunosuppressive medications.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Who should not take echinacea?</summary><p>Autoimmune conditions (lupus, RA, MS), immunosuppressive medication users, daisy-family allergy sufferers, children under 12 (without pediatric guidance), and pregnant/breastfeeding women should consult their provider.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How long does echinacea take to work?</summary><p>Immune cell activation begins within 2-4 hours. Preventive benefits develop over 1-2 weeks of daily use. For acute colds, greatest benefit when started within 24 hours of symptom onset.</p></details>

